In << f("raw.n_champions") >> years of NBA champions, none outscored its playoff opponents by more than the 2025–26 New York Knicks.
They went << f("raw.wins") >>-<< f("raw.losses") >>, posting the highest raw and opponent-adjusted margins on record, and they did it as underdogs: their regular season gave them only a << f("winprob.p_title", "{:.0f}") >>% chance to win the title at all.
This summary works through four questions: was the run historic and against real competition, does it hold up after adjusting for era and schedule, what made the Finals so different from the first three rounds, and how unlikely was a title run from where the Knicks started?

---

## 1. Yes, it was historic

![Opponent-adjusted playoff dominance: the 2025-26 Knicks' margin ranks first among << f("raw.n_champions") >> champions since 1983-84, the best single estimate rather than a settled #1.](../generated/images/knicks_2026_adjusted_margin_ranking.svg){#fig-adjusted-margin-ranking width=100%}

The Knicks' raw average margin of << f("raw.margin") >> points per game is the highest in << f("raw.n_champions") >> years of data, and adjusted for opponent strength their << f("adj.margin", "{:+.1f}") >> margin still ranks first, ahead of the 2016–17 Warriors (<< f("adj.top2.margin", "{:+.1f}") >>) and 1986–87 Lakers (<< f("adj.top3.margin", "{:+.1f}") >>).

**The objections up front, and the answers:**

- **A weak East?** No. The West–East strength gap in 2025–26 was only << f("gap.west_east") >> points per game (<< f("gap.pct", "{:.0f}") >>th percentile of West dominance); in << f("gap.pct_more_dominant") >> of prior seasons the West held a larger edge.
- **A soft bracket?** No. The Knicks' playoff opponents averaged an SRS (each team's season-long scoring margin, adjusted for schedule) of << f("adj.opp_srs") >>, right at the historical median for champions.
- **Padded by blowouts?** No. On a wins-only rating that never sees a point margin, the Knicks still rank first of << f("raw.n_champions") >>.
- **Injured opponents?** No. All four were essentially fully healthy (<< f("health.avg") >>% average availability; the Spurs and Hawks at << f("health.spurs") >>%).

They earned it by rising, not coasting.
Only the fifth-strongest team in the playoff field during the regular season, the Knicks made the biggest playoff jump of any 2026 team (a rise of << f("elev.knicks.elevation") >>, the << f("elev.knicks_rank") >>nd-biggest any champion has produced); the Spurs they beat in the Finals made the second-biggest jump in the field.

So how solid is that #1?
Six ways to measure dominance, six answers:

| How you measure dominance | What it adjusts for | Knicks rank |
|---|---|---|
| Raw scoring margin | nothing | 1st of << f("raw.n_champions") >> |
| Opponent-adjusted | strength of schedule | << f("ladder.rank_oppadj") >>st |
| Per possession | the era's pace | << f("pace.adj_rank") >>st |
| Scoring-share (raw margin, no opponent adjustment) | the era's scoring level (a harsh take) | 3rd |
| Era's spread | how top-heavy the league was | << f("spread.knicks_rank") >>th |
| Recency-weighted opponents (Elo) | opponents' late-season form | << f("elo.rank") >>rd |

Every *absolute* measure puts them first; the two *relative* ones, which grade against a deeper, more spread-out field than any champion faced, make it a top-five run rather than a clear first.
The scoring-share row is the crudest knock: 2025–26's high scoring is mostly sharper shooting, not a faster game, and the more accurate per-possession version keeps them first (<< f("pace.adj_per100", "{:+.1f}") >>).
That #1 is the best single guess, not a lock: re-drawing the 19 games leaves them first about << f("boot.p_rank1", "{:.0f}") >>% of the time, and the fairest test, which treats every past champion as just as uncertain as the Knicks, puts their chance of being the single best ever at about << f("hier.p_rank1", "{:.0f}") >>% (roughly a third to be top-five).
The verdict: one of the best handful of title runs ever, most likely the best by the raw numbers, but not provably the single best.

