## 3. Their regular season gave them a << f("winprob.p_title", "{:.0f}") >>% title chance

![How rare a << f("raw.wins") >>-<< f("raw.losses") >> run was: from the Knicks' regular season the model gave them a << f("winprob.p_title", "{:.0f}") >>% title shot, and a run this clean about << f("winprob.p_title_and_le3", "{:.0f}") >>%.](../generated/images/knicks_2026_title_run_rarity.svg){#fig-title-run-rarity width=100%}

Forget what happened and ask what the Knicks' regular season predicted.
A forecaster that knows only each team's regular-season strength and who had home court made New York a Finals underdog: the Spurs out-rated them over 82 games, so the model gave the Knicks about a << f("winprob.finals.p_series", "{:.0f}") >>% chance to win that series and only about a **<< f("winprob.p_title", "{:.0f}") >>% chance to win the title at all**.
A run as clean as << f("raw.wins") >>-<< f("raw.losses") >> was rarer still.
Only about << f("winprob.p_le3_given_title", "{:.0f}") >>% of the model's title runs lost three or fewer games, and barely **<< f("winprob.p_title_and_le3", "{:.0f}") >>%** of all simulated seasons produced both a championship and three or fewer losses.

Almost nothing about the regular season predicted this.
The Knicks were "supposed" to lose six or seven games on the way to a title they were not favored to win.
They lost three, and were seriously tested only in the Finals.

---

## The bottom line

By every adjusted measure tested, the 2026 Knicks rank at or near the top of NBA history, and their regular season gave them only a << f("winprob.p_title", "{:.0f}") >>% chance to get there.
The dominant first three rounds were real: the schedule was average, opponents were healthy, and the East was competitive.
The Spurs were the best-performing team they faced, and the Finals could have gone either way.
New York won it anyway.

